Paladins are oathbound divine warrior-defenders who split from the Cleric tradition during the Sundering Wars, when mortal armies desecrated temples and the high clerics who resolved never to leave sanctuaries defenseless again forsook pure ministry without abandoning faith. The foundational organizational principle is that the oath is the institution — sworn to the light itself rather than to any king or organization, overriding loyalty to commanders and civil authorities when covenant and command conflict. The oath-mark system inscribed in holy silver creates a genuine covenant relationship between practitioner and divine principle; advanced formation training is organized around historical case studies of conflicts between covenant requirements and institutional authority, including cases where Paladins exercised oath-authority against institutional directives and were retrospectively wrong. The tradition's operational style — advance-and-sanctify, closing distance to hold formation and punish evil with sanctified steel — is an extension of the foundational shield-warden logic to mobile contexts: advance in order to extend the ground that sacred practice can safely occupy, sanctify as you advance so the held ground is genuinely protected. The Paladin-Priest partnership is operationally necessary but requires continuous timing calibration: Paladin advance creates the secure ground within which Priest healing operations can sustain, and a Paladin who advances too aggressively leaves the Priest's position exposed. The tradition's internal archive of the Sundering Wars temple desecration events includes documentation of predecessor institutions of the five cities that those cities' Continuity factions would prefer classified — creating a persistent constraint on how aggressively those factions pursue historical suppression objectives.

