---
Midgaard registers Paladins through the Temple Authority's Oath Compact, requiring formal documentation of covenant commitments and Office of Sacred Warrant review of operations conducted under oath-authority.
The Continuity faction values the Paladin tradition as an institutional stability asset: oath-bound practitioners who will not compromise covenant requirements are predictable and useful even when specific requirements are inconvenient.
The more significant tension is the Paladin archive: Midgaard's predecessor institutions countersigned sealed warrants authorizing military forces' use of sacred spaces during the Sundering Wars, and the Paladin documentation of those events is more complete and less curated than what Midgaard's Registry contains.
The Office of Sacred Warrant review process is sometimes deployed as a procedural delay mechanism when Paladins operating under covenant requirements create political complications for Continuity faction interests.
The Reckoning faction's relationship with the Paladin tradition is warmer; Reckoning uses the archive's existence as leverage against Continuity's historical suppression agenda.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Jade Magistracy classifies Paladins under Gold jurisdiction with secondary Crimson filing for advance-and-sanctify operations in public spaces.
The Magistracy is specifically interested in whether Paladin operations that disrupt spiritual anomalies during crisis events will be coordinated with Magistracy crisis response or conducted unilaterally.
The historical tension is that Paladin oath-authority explicitly overrides institutional directives when covenant requires it, conflicting with the Magistracy's preference for unified command during crisis events.
Kowloon's founding narrative involves a collective covenant response to crisis; Paladins who frame their oath-authority as consistent with collective covenant responsibility rather than competing with it find institutional accommodation easier to secure.
The Harbor Syndic has a standing coordination protocol with registered Paladins for spiritual-anomaly situations in dock district areas.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess's Wall Command regards Paladins as high-value defensive assets for breach situations and consecration operations following frontier incursions that leave spiritual residue requiring clearance.
The advance-and-sanctify doctrine aligns well with Wall Command's preparedness culture: Paladins advance into breached areas to clear and hold while consecrating reclaimed ground, reducing recovery time before the Wall resumes full function.
Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant framework protects Paladins whose covenant requirements might conflict with Wall Command operational orders, without requiring them to invoke oath-authority directly.
Wall Command assessors evaluate Paladin capability by breach-holding capacity and consecration throughput.
Kiess's frontier context means Paladins accumulate genuine operational experience in high-intensity situations rather than ceremonial and civil contexts.

flags RAKUEN
---
Rakuen's Ember Wardens have a formal integration protocol for Paladin practitioners — unusual, as most Warden organizations treat Paladins as allied but separate.
The protocol exists because Rakuen's chronic emergency posture creates regular situations where simultaneous advance-and-sanctify and healing-and-ward maintenance are required without sufficient Paladin-Priest pairs available.
The communal burden-sharing ethos makes the Paladin's oath-bound commitment to collective welfare legible and valued: oath-to-covenant is understood as a recognizable form of community service.
The formal integration protocol establishes coordination standards letting both institutions operate without undermining each other during compound emergencies.

flags MAFDET
---
Mafdet registers Paladins through the Harbor Ledger House's oath obligation system — a natural fit, as covenant oaths are a form the Ledger House recognizes as legitimate.
The Ledger House distinguishes covenant oaths (sworn to a divine principle) from commercial oaths (sworn to a specific party for a specific obligation): Paladins carry both simultaneously when operating under commission agreements, and the Ledger House requires clear documentation of which oath governs when they conflict.
The Swift Court is relevant because Mafdet's commercial-claim adjudication framework is sometimes used to contest Paladin operations that disrupted commercial activity in the course of a covenant-required action.
The Shrine of the First Claw has generally ruled that legitimate covenant obligations preempt commercial liability in cases where commercial claims conflict with covenant requirements.

flags MIDGAARD KHENARI
---
Khenari theology frames death administration as a nine-stage lawful descent; Paladin advance-and-sanctify doctrine asserts the right to clear spiritual anomalies, which can include entities Khenari would classify as incomplete descents requiring formal processing rather than sanctified steel.
A Paladin who destroys an entity that a Khenari jurist-priest would classify as an open descent case has closed the case by force rather than procedure.
The Paladin tradition's response — that covenant authority to clear evil supersedes administrative procedure when the entity is actively threatening sacred ground — is theologically coherent but produces Khenari formal protests through the Temple Authority's Office of Sacred Warrant review.
The most functional arrangement in Midgaard is a coordination protocol in which Paladins advancing into spiritually compromised areas notify the nearest Khenari death-ledger office, which dispatches a rapid descent-completion team to process entities before the Paladin engages them where operationally possible.

flags MAFDET USHABTI
---
Ushabti frame cosmic events as legal adjudications: death is a completed verdict, spiritual anomalies are appeals in progress.
The Paladin's advance-and-sanctify doctrine asserts authority to clear entities whose presence violates covenant-protected ground, which Ushabti can read as enforcement of verdicts that have been improperly appealed.
In Mafdet, this alignment creates natural institutional partnership: Ushabti legal-verdict framing and Paladin covenant-authority both provide grounds for action against the same categories of entities, from different doctrinal positions reaching compatible practical conclusions.
The Harbor Ledger House has processed joint oath registrations in which a Paladin practitioner and Ushabti legal advocate coordinated covenant authority and verdict-enforcement authority to ensure Paladin clearance operations in spiritually compromised harbor areas produced legally defensible outcomes that Ushabti advocacy could uphold in Swift Court proceedings.
